**`const`** declares a variable that **cannot be reassigned**. Once assigned, the reference cannot change.

```typescript
const name = 'Alice';
name = 'Bob';  // ❌ ERROR: Assignment to constant variable

const user = { name: 'Alice' };
user.name = 'Bob';  // ✅ OK (object contents can change)
user = {};          // ❌ ERROR (cannot reassign)
```

**`let`** declares a variable that **can be reassigned**. Use it when the value will change.

```typescript
let count = 0;
count++;  // ✅ OK
```

**`var`** is the old way with **function scope** (not block scope), causing bugs. **Never use it.**

```typescript
if (true) {
    var x = 10;
}
console.log(x);  // 10 (leaked out of block!)

if (true) {
    let y = 20;
}
console.log(y);  // ❌ ERROR (block-scoped)
```

**Why prefer const:**
1. Prevents accidental reassignment
2. Makes code more predictable
3. Shows intent (this value won't change)
4. Use `let` only when you need to reassign

**Destructuring** extracts values from arrays or objects into separate variables.

**Array Destructuring:**

```typescript
const colors = ['red', 'green', 'blue'];

// Without destructuring
const first = colors[0];
const second = colors[1];

// With destructuring
const [first, second, third] = colors;
console.log(first);  // 'red'

// React example (useState)
const [count, setCount] = useState<number>(0);
```

**Object Destructuring:**

```typescript
const user = { name: 'Alice', age: 25, email: 'alice@example.com' };

// Without destructuring
const name = user.name;
const age = user.age;

// With destructuring
const { name, age, email } = user;

// With default values
const { name, age, role = 'user' } = user;
```

**In React Props (most common pattern):**

```tsx
// ❌ Without destructuring
function Greeting(props) {
    return <h1>Hello, {props.name}!</h1>;
}

// ✅ With destructuring (clean!)
function Greeting({ name, age }) {
    return (
        <div>
            <h1>Hello, {name}!</h1>
            <p>Age: {age}</p>
        </div>
    );
}

// With default values
function Button({ label = 'Click me', variant = 'primary' }) {
    return <button className={variant}>{label}</button>;
}
```

The **spread operator (`...`)** expands arrays or objects.

**Arrays:**

```typescript
const nums = [1, 2, 3];
const moreNums = [4, 5];

// Combine arrays
const all = [...nums, ...moreNums];  // [1, 2, 3, 4, 5]

// Copy array
const copy = [...nums];  // [1, 2, 3]

// Add elements
const extended = [...nums, 4, 5];  // [1, 2, 3, 4, 5]
```

**Objects:**

```typescript
const user = { name: 'Alice', age: 25 };
const updates = { age: 26, city: 'NYC' };

// Merge objects (later values override)
const updated = { ...user, ...updates };
// { name: 'Alice', age: 26, city: 'NYC' }

// Copy object
const copy = { ...user };

// Override specific property
const withEmail = { ...user, email: 'alice@example.com' };
```

**Why it's critical in React:**

React requires **immutable state updates** — you cannot mutate state directly:

```tsx
const [user, setUser] = useState({ name: 'Alice', age: 25 });

// ❌ WRONG: Mutating state directly
user.age = 26;  // React won't detect the change!

// ✅ CORRECT: Create new object with spread
setUser({ ...user, age: 26 });

// Array example
const [items, setItems] = useState([1, 2, 3]);

// ❌ WRONG
items.push(4);  // Mutates original array

// ✅ CORRECT
setItems([...items, 4]);  // New array
```

Spread creates a new object/array, triggering React's re-render.
